<section class=3D"section main-article-chapter" data-menu-title=3D"Binary v=
s. decimal">
 <h2 class=3D"section-title"><i class=3D"icon" data-icon=3D"1"></i>Binary v=
s. decimal</h2>
 <p>Since the binary system uses only two digits or bits and represents num=
bers using varying patterns of 1s and 0s, it is known as a <i>base-2 </i>sy=
stem. The digit 1 refers to "on" or "true," while 0 refers to "off" or "fal=
se."</p>
 <p>In contrast, the decimal numbering system is a <i>base-10 </i>system, w=
here each possible place in a number can be one of 10 digits (0-9). In a mu=
ltidigit number, the rightmost digit is in the first place, the digit next =
to it on the left is in 10th place, the digit further left is in 100th plac=
e and so on.</p>
 <p>For example, in the four-digit number 1,980, these are the places occup=
ied by each digit:</p>
