    <td style=3D"width: 48.0pt;"> <p>64</p> </td>=20
    <td style=3D"width: 48.0pt;"> <p>128</p> </td>=20
   </tr>=20
  </tbody>=20
 </table>
 <p>As the bit position increases from one to eight, the previous decimal v=
alue is multiplied by two. That's why the first bit has a value of 1, the s=
econd bit has a value of 2, the third bit has a value of 4 and so on.</p>
 <p>The final value of the decimal number is calculated by adding the indiv=
idual values from the above table. However, only those values where the bit=
 equals 1 should be added. These values represent the "on" position. The 0s=
 represent the "off" position, so they are not counted in the decimal value=
 calculation.</p>
 <p>So, for the binary number 01101000, the decimal value is calculated as:=
</p>
 <p>8 + 32 + 64 =3D 104</p>
